\begin{abstract}
Erd\H{o}s, Ordman, and Zalcstein~\cite{EOZ1993} showed that partitioning
the edges of a chordal graph on $n$ vertices into cliques may require as
many as $n^2/6$ cliques, exhibited a split graph achieving this, and proved
an upper bound of $(1-c)n^2/4$ for some $c>0$.  They left open whether
$n^2/6+O(n)$ cliques always suffice.

This note records a self-contained exact computation for the \EOZ{}
split family and a conditional upper bound under wCDH.
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\arabic*),leftmargin=2em]
  \item \textbf{(Self-contained exact computation.)} We give an explicit
    LP dual certificate showing that the \EOZ{} lower-bound family
    $G_m=\Sp(K_m,I_{2m})$ satisfies $\cp(G_m)=\frac{3m^2+m}{2}=
    \frac{n^2}{6}+\frac{n}{6}$ exactly for $n=3m$, together with a
    matching $1$-factorisation construction.
    We make no novelty claim for the existence of this lower-bound family;
    the purpose is to give a self-contained exact computation for the
    specific family used here.

  \item \textbf{(Conditional upper bound.)} If $G$ satisfies the
    \emph{weak Clique-Drop Hypothesis} (wCDH) --- namely, if there exists
    a maximum clique $K$ such that $\omega(G-E(K))\ge\omega(G)-1$ ---
    then $\cp(G)\le n^2/6+O(n)$.  We prove this in full; the exact bound
    is $(2n-1)^2/24+2$.  The hypothesis is not universal: it fails for
    $G_m$ itself, so the open problem remains.
\end{enumerate}
The conditional theorem has been independently verified in the proof
assistant Lean~\cite{Wouter2026}.
\end{abstract}

