\section{Introduction and background}
\label{sec:intro}

A \emph{clique edge-partition} (CEP) of a graph $G=(V,E)$ is a collection
of complete subgraphs whose edge sets partition $E(G)$; $\cp(G)$ denotes
the minimum number of cliques used.  A graph is \emph{chordal} if every
induced cycle has length exactly~$3$; equivalently it admits a
\emph{perfect elimination ordering} (PEO), a linear ordering $v_1,\dots,v_n$
such that $\Nplus(v_i):=N(v_i)\cap\{v_{i+1},\dots,v_n\}$ is a clique for
every $i$.

\subsection*{The \EOZ{} results and open problem}

The problem of bounding $\cp(G)$ for chordal graphs was studied by
\EOZ{}~\cite{EOZ1993}.  They proved:

\begin{backgroundbox}
\noindent\textbf{Known results~\cite{EOZ1993}.}
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*),nosep]
  \item There exists a chordal graph on $n$ vertices requiring $n^2/6$
    cliques in any CEP.  The example is a split graph (and threshold graph).
  \item For every chordal graph $G$ on $n$ vertices,
    $\cp(G)\le(1-c)n^2/4$ for some absolute constant $c>0$.
\end{enumerate}
They left open: is $\cp(G)\le n^2/6+O(n)$ for every chordal $G$?
\end{backgroundbox}

Let $f(n):=\max\{\cp(G): G\text{ chordal on }n\text{ vertices}\}$.  The
\EOZ{} results give $n^2/6-O(n)\le f(n)\le (1-c)n^2/4$.  The open problem
is whether $f(n)=n^2/6+O(n)$.

\subsection*{Our contributions}

We do not resolve the open problem.  We record two points.

\textbf{Self-contained exact computation.} The \EOZ{} paper exhibits a
split graph achieving $n^2/6$.  We give an LP dual certificate that
determines $\cp(G_m)$ exactly (\cref{sec:lower}), and a matching explicit
CEP construction.  The exact value is $\cp(G_m)=(3m^2+m)/2=n^2/6+n/6$
for $n=3m$.  We make no novelty claim for the existence of this
lower-bound family; we present a self-contained exact computation.

\textbf{Conditional upper bound.} We introduce a structural hypothesis
(wCDH, \cref{def:wcdh}) under which $\cp(G)\le n^2/6+O(n)$ can be proved
via a two-step compression argument (\cref{sec:conditional}).  Since wCDH
fails for $G_m$, the condition excludes the lower-bound family, and the open
problem remains for the wCDH-failing class.  The conditional theorem has
been independently formalized in Lean by W.~van Doorn~\cite{Wouter2026}.

\textbf{Warmup: the $n^2/4$ bound.} As preparation for the two-step
compression we also give a self-contained proof of the weaker $n^2/4$
bound via the PEO (\cref{sec:upper}).  This is weaker than what EOZ prove,
but the proof technique --- single-clique compression combined with the PEO
edge bound --- is the template for the conditional theorem.

