\section{Two failed approaches}
\label{sec:failed}

We document two natural attempts at an unconditional $n^2/6$ bound.

\subsection{Triangle--Forest partition (false)}

\noindent\textbf{Claimed lemma.} Every chordal $G$ admits edge-disjoint
triangles and a forest partitioning $E(G)$.

\begin{example}[$K_5$ counterexample]
$K_5$ is chordal.  Any two edge-disjoint triangles in $K_5$ leave four edges
forming a $4$-cycle (not a forest).  Three edge-disjoint triangles are
impossible: their union has all-even degrees, but $K_5$ minus one edge has two
odd-degree vertices.
\end{example}

\subsection{PEO triangle-packing algorithm (flawed bookkeeping)}

\begin{example}[$K_4$ and $G_3$ counterexamples]
A PEO algorithm matching pairs within $R_i=\{v_k\in\Nplus(v_i):v_iv_k
\notin\mathrm{PRECOV}\}$ produces $T=1$ triangle for $K_4$.  The claimed
bound $T\ge(m-n)/3=(6-4)/3$ holds, but for $G_3=\Sp(K_3,I_6)$ the
algorithm yields $T=3$ while $(m-n)/3=(21-9)/3=4>3$.  Moreover, the
bound $\cp(G)\le m/3+2n/3$ this implies gives $13$ for $G_3$, but
$\cp(G_3)=15>13$.
\end{example}

